07154nam a22008895i 9780857451170DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011000956  a97808574511707 a10.1515/97808574511702doi  a(DE-B1597)636025  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGN492b.P48 2011 7aSOC0020002bisacsh  aLB 49000qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90564:77200aPolicy Worlds :bAnthropology and the Analysis of Contemporary Power /ced. by Cris Shore, Susan Wright, Davide Però. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (348 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEASA Series ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Conceptualising Policy: Technologies of Governance and the Politics of Visibility -- tSection I Studying Policy: Methods, Paradigms, Perspectives -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 2 Illuminating the Apparatus: Steps toward a Nonlocal Ethnography of Global Governance -- tChapter 3 Politics and Ethics: Ethnographies of Expert Knowledge and Professional Identities -- tChapter 4 Peopling Policy: On Conflicting Subjectivities of Fee-Paying Students -- tChapter 5 ‘Studying Through’: A Strategy for Studying Political Transformation. Or Sex, Lies and British Politics -- tChapter 6 What was Neoliberalism and What Comes Next? The Transformation of Citizenship in the Law-and-Order State -- tSection II Studying Governance: Policy as a Window onto the Modern State -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 7 Intimate Knowledge and the Politics of Policy Convergence: The World Bank and Social Security Reform in Mexico -- tChapter 8 Shadow Governing: What the Neocon Core Reveals about Power and Influence in America -- tChapter 9 Espionage, Policy and the Art of Government: The British Secret Services and the War on Iraq -- tChapter 10 The (Un)Making of Policy in the Shadow of the World Bank: Infrastructure Development, Urban Resettlement and the Cunning State in India -- tChapter 11 Sweden’s National Pension System as a Political Technology -- tSection III Subjects of Policy: Construction and Contestation -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 12 The Case of Scanzano: Raison d’État and the Reasons for a Rebellion -- tChapter 13 Migrants’ Practices of Citizenship and Policy Change -- tChapter 14 Integration Policy and Ethnic Minority Associations -- tChapter 15 The Elephant in the Room: Multistakeholder Dialogue on Agricultural Biotechnology in the Food and Agriculture Organization -- tAfterword -- tChapter 16 A Policy Ethnographer’s Reading of Policy Anthropology -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are few areas of society today that remain outside the ambit of policy processes, and likewise policy making has progressively reached into the structure and fabric of everyday life. An instrument of modern government, policy and its processes provide an analytical window into systems of governance themselves, opening up ways to study power and the construction of regimes of truth. This volume argues that policies are not simply coercive, constraining or confined to static texts; rather, they are productive, continually contested and able to create new social and semantic spaces and new sets of relations. Anthropologists do not stand outside or above systems of governance but are themselves subject to the rhetoric and rationalities of policy. The analyses of policy worlds presented by the contributors to this volume open up new possibilities for understanding systems of knowledge and power and the positioning of academics within them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aPolitical anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Gener